# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-winchell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:alexander-winchell/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:alexander-winchell/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:alexander-winchell/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:alexander-winchell/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:alexander-winchell/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] Winchell was born in Minneapolis to Newton Horace and Charlotte Sophia.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] He was educated at the University of Minnesota with a BS in 1896 and MS in 1897 under Charles Peter Berkey.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] He then studied in Paris under Alfred Lacroix receiving a DSc in 1900.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] He then joined the Montana School of Mines and later the University of Wisconsin.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] He worked on applications of X-ray crystallography to mineralogy, working with Linus Pauling, W.H.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] He also consulted for the US Geological Survey, the American Cyanamid Company and was a visiting professor at the University of Virginia and Columbia University.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] Winchell married Clare Edith Christello in 1898 and they had five children, several of whom continued in geology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] After the death of Clare in 1932, he married his first cousin once removed Florence Mabel Sylvester (granddaughter of Alexander Winchell).
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-newton-winchell] He received the Roebling medal of the Mineralogical Society of America in 1955.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:alexander-winchell/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz was born in Swinemünde, Germany (now Świnoujście, Poland).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] He grew up and attended school in Breslau (now Wrocław).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] He was a friend of Carl Hauptmann, brother of the famous author Gerhart Hauptmann.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1879, he founded a secret racial youth society.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In Gerhart Hauptmann's drama *Vor Sonnenaufgang* ("Before Sunrise"), which was first performed on 20 October 1889 in Berlin, the key figure of the journalist Loth was based on Ploetz.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] After he had finished school, Ploetz at first studied political economy in Breslau, where he joined the "Freie Wissenschaftliche Vereinigung" (Free Scientific Union).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Among his friends were his brother, his former school friend Ferdinand Simon (later son-in-law of August Bebel), the brothers Carl and Gerhart Hauptmann, Heinrich Laux and Charles Proteus Steinmetz.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] The circle enthusiastically read the works of Ernst Haeckel and Charles Darwin.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Carl Hauptmann was a student of Haeckel, and Gerhart Hauptmann and Ploetz attended some of Haeckel's lectures.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] The group expanded and developed a plan of founding a colony in one of the Pacific states and established itself as the "Pacific Association".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] It planned a "community on friendly, socialist and maybe also pan-Germanic basis".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In consequence of the prosecution of socialistically-minded persons in application of Otto von Bismarck's antisocialist laws (1878–1890), Ploetz in 1883 fled to Zürich, where he continued to study political economy with Julius Platter (1844–1923).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In his memoirs, Ploetz stated as an important reason for his choice of Zürich that in his studies in Breslau, socialist theories had been only incidentally mentioned.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] After living for a half a year in the United States, Ploetz returned to Zürich and began to study medicine.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1886, he fell in love with a fellow student, Agnes Bluhm, but he was involved with Pauline Rüdin; the last two decided to get married early in 1887.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz was also seeing an American, Mary Sherwood, who was studying hypnotism.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1890, Ploetz became a medical doctor and married his former girlfriend Pauline, but they never had children.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Bluhm, however, kept Ploetz as a close friend throughout her life, and both shared similar views on racial purity and the benefits of eugenics.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz and his wife lived in the United States for four years and divorced in 1898.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz later married Anita Nordenholz, and they produced three children: Ulrich (called Uli), Cordelia (called Deda) and Wilfrid (called Fridl, 1912–2013).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz first proposed the theory of racial hygiene (race-based eugenics) in his "Racial Hygiene Basics" (*Grundlinien einer Rassenhygiene*) in 1895.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1907 the society became the "International Society for Racial Hygiene".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1930, he was made an honorary doctor of the Ludwig-Maximilians-Universität München and became a supporter of the Nazi Party, which was elected to power in 1933.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz wrote in April that year that he believed that Hitler would bring racial hygiene from its previous marginality into the mainstream.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1933, Reich Interior Minister Wilhelm Frick established an "expert advisory committee for population and racial policy", which included Ploetz, Fritz Lenz, Ernst Rüdin and Hans F.K.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] The expert advisory committee had the task of advising the Nazis on the implementation and enforcement of legislation regarding racial and eugenic issues.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1936, Hitler appointed Ploetz to a professorship.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In 1937, at the age of 77, he joined the Nazi Party.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] He died in 1940 at the age of 79 and is buried at his home in Herrsching on the Ammersee in Bavaria.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] After his death, Otmar Freiherr von Verschuer praised his "inner sympathy and enthusiasm [with] the National Socialist Movement".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ernst Rüdin, also a committed Nazi, had praised Ploetz two years earlier as a man "by his meritorious services has helped to set up our Nazi ideology".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In his book *The Excellence of Our Race and the Protection of the Weak* (1895), Ploetz coined the term "racial hygiene" (German: *Rassenhygiene*); he described a society in which eugenic ideas would be applied.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] The publication endorsed a Social Darwinist interpretation of race and solidified genetic determinist ideas about the "evolutionary superiority of the German *Volk*".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] It would examine the moral and intellectual capacity of citizens to decide on marriage and the permitted number of children.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] It might include a prohibition on reproduction by the "unfit".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Disabled children would be euthanized at birth, and all young persons would undergo an examination at puberty to determine if they would be permitted to marry and have children.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Society would be regulated strictly to ensure equal opportunity, and those who failed would starve.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz found the idea horrible and suggested a humane alternative of simply encouraging only "fit" people to reproduce, but he called that a weak proposal.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Along with many other eugenicists in Europe and America, Ploetz believed in the superiority of the Nordic race.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] His writings were a major influence on Nazi ideology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] His opinion of the Jewish question changed during the course of his life, but his view and the doctrine of the Nazi Party were in accord by the time it came to power in 1933.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] In his early writings, Ploetz credited Jews as the highest cultural race after Europeans.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] He stressed that the distinctiveness of Jews indicated that their mental characteristics would adversely affect Aryans by introducing individualism and lack of love for the military and the nation.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-ploetz] Ploetz favoured the global dominance of the Aryan race.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He was also known for his hatred and rejection of what he regarded as "negative" Christianity; however, he played an important role in the development of Nazi-aligned Positive Christianity, which rejected the Old Testament.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg was born on 12 January 1893 in Reval (now Tallinn, Estonia), then in the Governorate of Estonia of the Russian Empire.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] His mother Elfriede (née Siré), who had French and German ancestry, was the daughter of Louise Rosalie (née Fabricius), born near Leal (modern Lihula, Estonia) in 1842, and of the railway official Friedrich August Siré, born in Saint Petersburg, Russia, in 1843.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Born in the same city in 1868, Elfriede Siré received the Christian sacrament of Confirmation in Reval at 17 in 1885.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] She married Woldemar Wilhelm Rosenberg, a wealthy merchant from Reval, in the Lutheran Church of Saint Peter and Saint Paul (St-Petersburg) in 1886.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The young Rosenberg's mother died two months after his birth.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] His paternal grandfather, Martin Rosenberg, was a master shoemaker and elder of his craft guild.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Born in Riga in 1820, and probably partly of Latvian descent, he had moved to Reval in the 1850s, where he met Julie Elisabeth Stramm, born in Jörden (now Juuru, Estonia) in 1835.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Szell wrote that among Rosenberg's ancestors were only "Latvians, Jews, Mongols, and French." As a result of his open letter, Szell was deported by Lithuanian authorities on 15 September 1936.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] His claims were repeated in the 15 September 1937 issue of the Vatican newspaper *L'Osservatore Romano*.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] These allegations have not been substantiated by historical evidence and appear to have been politically motivated, as Rosenberg was born to a Baltic German father and an Estonian mother and did not have Jewish ancestry.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The young Rosenberg graduated from the Petri-Realschule (currently Tallinna Reaalkool) and enrolled in architecture studies at the Riga Polytechnical Institute in the autumn of 1910.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In 1915, as the German army was approaching Riga, the entire school evacuated to the Moscow Imperial Higher Technical School (Russian: Императорское Московское техническое училище (ИМТУ)), where he completed his PhD studies in 1917.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] During his stays at home in Reval, he attended the art studio of the famed painter Ants Laikmaa—though he showed promise, there are no records that he ever exhibited.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] During the German occupation of Estonia in 1918, Rosenberg served as a drawing teacher at the Gustav Adolf Gymnasium and Tallinna II Reaalkool (current Tallinn Polytechnic School).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He gave his first speech on "Jewish Marxism" on 30 November, at the House of the Blackheads, after the 28 November 1918 outbreak of the Estonian War of Independence.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He emigrated to Germany with the retreating Imperial German army, along with Max Scheubner-Richter, who served as something of a mentor to Rosenberg and to his ideology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Arriving in Munich, he contributed to Dietrich Eckart's publication, the *Völkischer Beobachter* (*Ethnic/Nationalist Observer*).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] By this time, he was both an antisemite – influenced by Houston Stewart Chamberlain's book *The Foundations of the Nineteenth Century*, one of the key proto-Nazi books of racial theory – and an anti-Bolshevik.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg became one of the earliest members of the German Workers' Party – later renamed the National Socialist German Workers' Party, better known as the Nazi Party – joining in January 1919, eight months before Adolf Hitler joined in September.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] According to some historians, Rosenberg had also been a member of the Thule Society, along with Eckart, although Nicholas Goodrick-Clarke contends that they were only guests.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The *Völkischer Beobachter* became the Nazi party newspaper in December 1920.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Eckart was its first editor and after his bout with alcoholism, Rosenberg became its editor in 1923.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg was a leading member of Aufbau Vereinigung, Reconstruction Organisation, a conspiratorial organisation of White Russian émigrés which had a critical influence on early Nazi policy.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In November 1923, after the failed Beer Hall Putsch, Hitler, who had been imprisoned for treason, appointed Rosenberg as the leader of the Nazi movement.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] However, at the time of the appointment Hitler had no reason to believe that he would soon be released, and Rosenberg had not appeared weak, so this may have been Hitler reading back into history his dissatisfaction with Rosenberg for the job he did.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] On 1 January 1924, Rosenberg founded the Greater German People's Community, a Nazi front organization.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Headquartered in Munich, it was largely limited to Bavaria, the birthplace of National Socialism, had no substantial presence outside that State and became a haven for Nazi Party members from that area.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Prominent members included Max Amann, Phillip Bouhler, Hermann Esser, Franz Xaver Schwarz and Julius Streicher.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg, one of the least charismatic of the Nazi leaders and lacking in leadership qualities, was soon pushed aside by Streicher, a far more ruthless and abrasive personality, who was elected Chairman on 9 July 1924 with Esser, also a coarse, bullying sort, as his Deputy Chairman.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg was on the rostrum at the refoundation of the NSDAP in February 1925.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In 1929 Rosenberg founded the Militant League for German Culture.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He later formed the "Institute for Research on the Jewish Question", the first branch of a projected Advanced School of the NSDAP, dedicated to identifying and attacking supposed Jewish influence in German culture and to recording the history of Judaism from a radical nationalist perspective.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In 1930, he published his philosophical book of racial theory *The Myth of the Twentieth Century* (*Der Mythus des 20.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Jahrhunderts*) which deals with key issues in the Nazi ideology, such as the "Jewish question".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He condemned Islam in the book as well which he described as being against European races and as anti-Christian.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg intended his book as a sequel to Houston Stewart Chamberlain's above-cited book.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Despite selling more than a million copies by 1945, its influence within Nazism remains doubtful.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] It is often said to have been a book that was officially venerated within Nazism, but one that few had actually read beyond the first chapter or even found comprehensible.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] According to Albert Speer, Hitler called it "stuff nobody can understand" and disapproved of its pseudo-religious tone.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Contradicting this, other authors noted that Hitler considered it the most important book of party ideology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg also played a key role in developing Hitler's belief in Jewish conspiracies by introducing him to The Protocols of the Elders of Zion.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg was elected as a *Reichstag* deputy at the September 1930 parliamentary election as a representative of the Nazi Party electoral list.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He would continue to serve in this capacity until the end of the Nazi regime, representing electoral constituency 33, Hesse-Darmstadt, from July 1932.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg helped convince Hitler, whose early speeches focused on revenge against France and Britain, that communism was a serious threat to Germany.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] "Jewish-Bolshevism" became an ideological target for Nazism during the early 1920s.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In Rome during November 1932 Rosenberg participated in the Volta Conference about Europe.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] British historian Sir Charles Petrie met him there and regarded him with great distaste; Petrie was a Catholic and strongly objected to Rosenberg's anti-Jewish and anti-Catholic sentiments.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The following year, following the Nazi seizure of power, Rosenberg was named leader of the Nazi Party's Foreign Policy Office in April, and on 2 June 1933 he was named a *Reichsleiter*, the second highest political rank in the Nazi Party.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In May 1933 Rosenberg visited Britain, to give the impression that the Nazis would not be a threat and to encourage links between the new regime and the British Empire.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] When Rosenberg laid a wreath bearing a swastika at the Cenotaph, James Edmond Sears, a Labour Party candidate, slashed it, later threw it in the Thames and was fined 40 shillings for willful damage at Bow Street magistrate's court.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In October 1933, Rosenberg was named as a member of Hans Frank's Academy for German Law.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] On 27 January 1934, Hitler made Rosenberg the "Führer's Representative for the Supervision of Intellectual and Ideological Education of the NSDAP." This was the origin of the Amt Rosenberg, or Rosenberg Office, which was an official body for cultural policy and surveillance within the Nazi party.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] It was also known as the Reich surveillance office.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The ERR were especially active in Paris in looting art stolen from famous Jewish families such as the Rothschilds and that of Paul Rosenberg.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Hermann Göring used the ERR to collect art for his own personal gratification.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He created a "Special Task Force for Music" (*Sonderstab Musik*) to collect the best musical instruments and scores for use in a university to be built in Hitler's home town of Linz, Austria.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The orders given to the *Sonderstab Musik* were to loot all forms of Jewish property in Germany and of those found in any country taken over by the German army, and any musical instruments or scores were to be immediately shipped to Berlin.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Following the invasion of the USSR, Rosenberg was appointed head of the Reich Ministry for the Occupied Eastern Territories (*Reichsministerium für die besetzten Ostgebiete*) on 17 July 1941.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Alfred Meyer served as his deputy and represented him at the Wannsee Conference.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Another official of the Ministry, Georg Leibbrandt, also attended the conference, at Rosenberg's request.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg had presented Hitler with his plan for the organization of the conquered Eastern territories, suggesting the establishment of new administrative districts, to replace the previously Soviet-controlled territories with new Reichskommissariats.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] They would provide a buffer against Soviet expansion in preparation for the total eradication of Communism and Bolshevism by decisive pre-emptive military action.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Following these plans, when Wehrmacht forces invaded Soviet-controlled territory, they immediately implemented the first of the proposed Reichskommissariats of Ostland and Ukraine, under the leadership of Hinrich Lohse and Erich Koch, respectively.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The organization of these administrative territories led to conflict between Rosenberg and the SS over the treatment of Slavs under German occupation.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] As Nazi Germany's chief racial theorist, Rosenberg considered Slavs, though lesser than Germans, to be Aryan.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg often complained to Hitler and Himmler about the treatment of non-Jewish occupied peoples.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He proposed the creation of buffer satellite states made out of Greater Finland, Baltica, Ukraine, and Caucasus.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] At the Nuremberg trials he said he was ignorant of the Holocaust, despite the fact that Leibbrandt and Meyer were present at the Wannsee conference.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Since the invasion of the Soviet Union intended to impose the New Order, it was essentially a war of conquest.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] German propaganda efforts designed to win over Russian opinion were, at best, patchy and inconsistent.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Alfred Rosenberg was one of the few in the Nazi hierarchy who advocated a policy designed to encourage anti-Communist opinion among the population of the occupied territories.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] His interest here was mainly in the non-Russian areas such as Ukraine and the Baltic States; however, supporters of the Russian Liberation Army were somewhat able to win him over.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Amongst other things, Rosenberg issued a series of posters announcing the end of the Soviet collective farms (*kolkhoz*).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He also issued an Agrarian Law in February 1942, annulling all Soviet legislation on farming and restoring family farms for those willing to collaborate with the occupiers.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] But decollectivisation conflicted with the wider demands of wartime food production, and Hermann Göring demanded that the collective farms be retained, save for a change of name.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Hitler himself denounced the redistribution of land as "stupid".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] There were numerous German armed forces (*Wehrmacht*) posters asking for assistance in the *Bandenkrieg,* the war against the Soviet partisans, though, once again, German policy had the effect of adding to their problems.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Posters for "volunteer" labour, with inscriptions such as "Come work with us to shorten the war", hid the appalling realities faced by Russian workers in Germany.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg noted that many joined the partisans when volunteers for work details declined and the Germans resorted to force to acquire workers from the East.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg was captured by Allied troops on 19 May 1945 in Flensburg-Mürwik.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He was tried at Nuremberg and found guilty of all four counts: conspiracy to commit crimes against peace; planning, initiating and waging wars of aggression; war crimes; and crimes against humanity.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The final judgment against him named him one of the principal planners of the invasion of Norway and the invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] It also held him directly responsible for the systematic plunder of the occupied countries of Europe, as well as the brutal conditions in Eastern Europe.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] During his trial he wrote his memoirs, which were published posthumously and with analytical commentary by Serge Lang and Ernst von Schenck.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He was sentenced to death and executed with other condemned co-defendants at Nuremberg Prison on the morning of 16 October 1946.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] His body, like those of the other nine executed men and that of Hermann Göring, was cremated at Ostfriedhof (Munich) and the ashes were scattered in the river Isar.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Throughout the trial, it was agreed that Rosenberg had a decisive role in shaping Nazi philosophy and ideology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] According to Joseph Kingsbury-Smith, who covered the executions for the International News Service, Rosenberg was the only condemned man who, when asked at the gallows if he had any last statement to make, replied with only one word: "No".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Hitler was a leader oriented towards practical politics, whereas, for Rosenberg, religion and philosophy were key and he was the most culturally influential within the party.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Several accounts of the time before the Nazi ascension to power speak of Hitler as being a mouthpiece for Rosenberg's views, and he clearly exerted a great deal of intellectual influence.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] The question of Rosenberg's influence in the Nazi Party is controversial.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He was perceived as lacking the charisma and political skills of the other Nazi leaders, and was somewhat isolated.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In some of his speeches Hitler appeared to be close to Rosenberg's views, rejecting traditional Christianity as a religion based on Jewish culture, preferring an ethnically and culturally pure "Race" whose destiny was supposed to be assigned to the German people by "Providence".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] But Hitler rejected Rosenberg's spiritual views on race and instead based his views on biology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] After Hitler's assumption of power he moved to unify the churches into a national church which could be manipulated and controlled.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He placed himself in the position of being the man to save Positive Christianity from utter destruction at the hands of the atheistic antitheist Communists of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] This was especially true immediately before and after the elections of 1932; Hitler wanted to appear non-threatening to major Christian faiths and consolidate his power.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Some Nazi leaders, such as Martin Bormann, were anti-Christian and sympathetic to Rosenberg.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Once in power, Hitler and most Nazi leaders sought to unify the Christian denominations in favor of "positive Christianity".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Hitler privately condemned mystical and pseudoreligious interests as "nonsense", and maintained that National Socialism was based on science and should avoid mystic and cultic practices.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Heinrich Himmler's views were among the closest to Rosenberg's, and their estrangement was perhaps created by Himmler's abilities to put into action what Rosenberg had only written.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Also, while Rosenberg thought Christianity should be allowed to die out, Himmler actively set out to create countering pagan rituals.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] As the Nazi Party's chief racial theorist, Rosenberg oversaw the construction of a human racial "ladder" that justified Hitler's racial and ethnic policies.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg built on the works of Arthur de Gobineau, Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Madison Grant and the Klansman Lothrop Stoddard as well as on the beliefs of Hitler.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg placed Blacks and Jews at the very bottom of the ladder, while at the very top stood the "Aryan" race.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg promoted the Nordic theory which considered the Nordic race the "master race", superior to all others, including to other Aryans (Indo-Europeans).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg got the racial term *Untermensch* from the title of Stoddard's 1922 book *The Revolt Against Civilization: The Menace of the Under-men*, which had been adopted by the Nazis from that book's German version *Der Kulturumsturz: Die Drohung des Untermenschen* (1925).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg reshaped the Nazi racial policy over the years, but it always consisted of Aryan supremacy, extreme German nationalism and rabid antisemitism.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg also outspokenly opposed homosexuality – notably in his pamphlet "Der Sumpf" ("The Swamp", 1927).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He viewed homosexuality as a hindrance to the expansion of the "racially pure" Nordic population.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg's attitude towards Slavs was flexible because it depended on the particular nation which he referred to.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] As a result of the ideology of "Drang nach Osten" ("Drive to the East"), Rosenberg saw his mission as the conquest and colonization of the Slavic East.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In *The Myth of the Twentieth Century*, Rosenberg describes Russian Slavs as being overwhelmed by Bolshevism.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Regarding Ukrainians, he favoured setting up a buffer state to ease the pressure on the German eastern frontier, while agreeing with the notion that Russia could be exploited for the benefit of Germany.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] During the war, Rosenberg was in favour of collaboration with the East Slavs against Bolshevism and offering them national independence unlike other Nazis such as Hitler and Himmler who dismissed such ideas.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg criticised those who did not subscribe to his racial theories.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] For example, he attacked Fascist Italy for what he perceived as its incorrect and improper stance on race and Jewishness.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg was raised as a Lutheran, but he rejected what he called "negative" Christianity later in life.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Instead, Rosenberg argued for a new "religion of the blood", which was based on the supposed innate promptings of the Nordic soul to defend its noble character against racial and cultural degeneration.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In his 1920 book *Immorality in the Talmud*, Rosenberg identified Jews with the antichrist.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg stated that "The general ideas of the Roman and of the Protestant churches are negative Christianity and do not, therefore, accord with our (German) soul." His support for Martin Luther as a great German figure was always ambivalent.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In January 1934, Hitler appointed Rosenberg cultural and educational leader of the Reich.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Rosenberg has been described as an atheist by some people, including Henry F.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Gerecke, the Lutheran chaplain who communed with some of the Nuremberg prisoners with Lutheran backgrounds, like Joachim von Ribbentrop and Wilhelm Keitel.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Gustave Mark Gilbert, Rosenberg's prison psychologist during his trial, reports that Rosenberg described himself having "always been anti-Catholic" and criticised the Church's power.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Due to his criticism of traditional Christianity, some polemical texts have called him a neo-pagan.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] During the Nuremberg trials, Rosenberg's handwritten diary was translated by Harry Fiss, Chief of Documentation for the American prosecution.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] After its use in evidence during the Nuremberg trials, the diary went missing, along with other material which had been given to the prosecutor Robert Kempner (1899–1993).
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Kempner had taken the diary, along with several other documents pertaining to the Nazi prosecutions back to his home.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] This was considered to be against standard government procedure, and illegal.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] It was recovered in Lewiston, N.Y., on 13 June 2013 after a lengthy investigation by the United States Department of Homeland Security.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Written on 425 loose-leaf pages, with entries dating from 1936 through 1944, it is now the property of the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum (USHMM) in Washington.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Former Federal Bureau of Investigation agent Robert King Wittman, who helped track down the diary, said, "there is no place in the diary where we have Rosenberg or Hitler saying the Jews should be exterminated, all it said was 'move them out of Europe'".
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] *The New York Times* said of the search for the missing manuscript that "the tangled journey of the diary could itself be the subject of a television mini-series." Since the end of 2013, the USHMM has shown the 425-page document (photos and transcripts) on its homepage.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] In 1915, he married Hilda Leesmann, an ethnic Estonian; they divorced in 1923.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] Two years later, in 1925 he married Hedwig Kramer, to whom he remained wed until his execution by the Allies.
[src:alexander-winchell/alfred-rosenberg] He and Kramer had two children: a son who died in infancy and a daughter, Irene, who was born in 1930.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] Alice was the daughter of Charles Thomas Brues, an entomologist at Harvard University and her botanist mother, Beirne Barrett Brues.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] Alice was a naturalist who specialised in botany.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] During her youth she was often assigned the task of collecting insects from plants by her parents and her mother in 1924 published a diary work of the families observations.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] In 1933, Alice graduated from Bryn Mawr College, majoring in philosophy and psychology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] Later studying under Earnest Hooton, she obtained a PhD from Harvard in 1940 in physical anthropology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] Her first job was as a research associate at the Peabody Museum at Harvard, and later as a consulting anthropologist with the Chemical Corps.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] In 1946 she took the position as an assistant professor of Anatomy at the University of Oklahoma School of Medicine, later promoted to full professor in 1960.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] She also was curator of physical anthropology at Stovall Museum in Norman, Okla., (1956–65) and a staff member with the Southwestern Homicide Investigators Seminar (1954–65).
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] While a curator of physical anthropology at the University of Oklahoma School of Medicine, she contributed to the fields of paleopathology and forensic anthropology.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] In 1965, Brues was recruited to the anthropology department at the University of Colorado at Boulder, where she remained until her retirement in 1984.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] She received three awards for outstanding achievement, one from each of the professional associations of which she was a member: the American Association of Physical Anthropology (AAPA), the Human Biology Association and the American Academy of Forensic Sciences.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] She was associate editor of the *American Journal of Physical Anthropology* for four years, a member of the AAPA executive board for three years, AAPA vice president from 1966 to 1968 and AAPA president from 1971 to 1973.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] She was a member of the executive committee of the Human Biology Council and the council's vice president in 1976–77.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] She also was a member of the advisory council of the National Institute of Dental Research (1972–75) and of the fellowship review committee for the National Institute of Mental Health (1976–77).
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] She published over 300 scientific articles, and several books, most notably *People and Races* (1977).
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] Alice dedicated this work to her father, crediting him with teaching her to “think biologically” at a very early age.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] The work was one of the last to be published on race from a mostly physical anthropological perspective in the vein of Carleton Coon (whom Brues also worked with) and it was republished in 1990.
[src:alexander-winchell/alice-mossie-brues] It received some positive reviews, although others were mixed to negative.
